        <section id="troubleshooting" class="content-section">
          <h2>Troubleshooting Common Problems</h2>
          <p>Understanding common binocular problems and solutions enables quick diagnosis and appropriate remedies. Some issues resolve through simple user adjustments; others require professional repair.</p>

          <h3>Blurry or Soft Images</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause 1 - Incorrect Diopter Setting:</strong> Solution: Recalibrate diopter adjustment. Cover right objective, focus left eye using center focus wheel until sharp, then cover left objective and adjust diopter ring until right eye sharp. This compensates for vision differences between eyes.</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 2 - Dirty Lenses:</strong> Solution: Clean objective and eyepiece lenses following proper procedure. Even light dust accumulation degrades sharpness noticeably.</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 3 - Internal Condensation:</strong> Solution: Allow binoculars to reach ambient temperature gradually. Store in dry environment with desiccant. For waterproof models with internal fogging, professional service required—seal breach allows moisture entry.</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 4 - Optical Defect or Separation:</strong> Solution: Internal element separation or coating degradation requires professional service. Indicated by persistent softness across entire field regardless of focus adjustment.</p>

          <h3>Double Images or Eye Strain</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause - Collimation Error:</strong> Solution: Test collimation using methods described in collimation section. Minor errors sometimes compensated by eye muscle adjustment (causes strain). Significant errors require professional collimation service. Verify collimation before attempting other troubleshooting.</p>

          <h3>Stiff Focus Mechanism</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause 1 - Dirt or Grit:</strong> Solution: Gently clean visible portions of focus mechanism with soft brush removing debris. If contamination internal, professional service required.</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 2 - Lubricant Stiffening:</strong> Solution: In cold weather, allow binoculars to warm gradually before use. If permanent stiffness, professional relubrication needed ($30-$60).</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 3 - Mechanical Damage:</strong> Solution: If focus mechanism damaged (dropped binoculars, hard impact), professional repair required. Avoid forcing stiff focus preventing further damage.</p>

          <h3>One Eye Blurry Despite Focus Adjustment</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause - Diopter Setting Lost:</strong> Solution: Recalibrate diopter following proper procedure. Many binoculars' diopter rings turn easily during use requiring periodic recalibration. Some models offer locking diopter rings preventing inadvertent adjustment.</p>

          <h3>Dark Crescents or Shadows in Field</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause 1 - Incorrect Eye Position:</strong> Solution: Adjust binoculars-to-eye distance. Too far from eyes causes vignetting (dark crescents). Position eyes at proper eye relief distance (varies by model, typically 14-18mm).</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 2 - Incorrect Interpupillary Distance:</strong> Solution: Adjust interpupillary distance matching your eye spacing. Improper IPD setting causes dark shadows or partial field blockage.</p>

          <p><strong>Cause 3 - Eyecup Position:</strong> Solution: Adjust eyecups to proper extension—full extension for non-eyeglass wearers, retracted for eyeglass wearers. Incorrect eyecup position causes vignetting.</p>

          <h3>Rattling or Loose Components</h3>
          <p><strong>Cause - Mechanical Loosening:</strong> Solution: Identify loose component. Eyecups sometimes unscrew from normal use—tighten carefully. Internal rattling indicates component dislodgment requiring professional service. Transport vibration sometimes loosens screws; tighten external screws carefully avoiding overtightening. Internal loose components require professional repair.</p>
